# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 29, 1776.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The delegate from Hanover County Patrick Henry defeated Thomas Nelson Jr. and John Page.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election took place forty-five days after the adoption of the Lee Resolution by the Fifth Virginia Convention declaring the independence of the United Colonies from Great Britain.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Constitution of Virginia had been adopted by the convention the same day and went into effect immediately.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The new constitution called for the governor of Virginia to be elected by the votes of the Virginia General Assembly meeting in joint session.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Virginia Convention, as the provisional legislature of the commonwealth, performed this function in the election of 1776.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Prior to 1830, the governor served a term of one year, renewable no more than three times in a seven-year period.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Henry was reelected four times: twice consecutively in 1777 and 1778, and again in 1784 and 1785, to serve a total of five consecutive terms in office.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Fifth Virginia Convention convened in Williamsburg on May 6, 1776, amidst increasingly widespread support for independence among the Patriots who supported the American Revolution.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] On May 15, 1776, the convention approved a resolution instructing Virginia's delegates in the Second Continental Congress to support a formal declaration of independence absolving the Thirteen Colonies from their allegiance to the British Empire.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Congress voted to adopt the Lee Resolution on July 2, precipitating passage of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] While Congress debated independence, the Virginia Convention took action to establish the foundations for an independent commonwealth.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A Declaration of Rights was introduced in the convention on May 27 and adopted on June 12; on June 29, the delegates voted unanimously to adopt the proposed Constitution of Virginia.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] With the Constitution now in place, elections for governor and Attorney General proceeded immediately.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Constitution of 1776 called for the governor and other executive officers to be elected by a joint session of the General Assembly, with a majority of votes cast necessary to elect the governor.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The governor was elected for a term of one year and limited to three terms in a seven-year period.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] With the first General Assembly yet unelected, the Virginia Convention carried out the election of the first governor and Attorney General.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election was conducted by secret ballot; in all, 106 delegates to the Virginia Convention cast votes for governor.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Virginia Convention elected Henry by a majority of 60 electoral votes to 45 for his nearest competitor, Thomas Nelson.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] George Wythe, James Madison, Bartholomew Dandridge, and William Roscoe Wilson Curl were appointed to inspect the ballots and inform Henry of his election.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was scheduled to be held in Virginia on May 29, 1777.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election] However, when the Virginia General Assembly met to conduct the election, the incumbent governor of Virginia Patrick Henry was the only candidate nominated.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election] By a joint resolution of the Senate and House of Delegates, balloting was dispensed with and Henry was declared re-elected by acclamation.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1778-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was scheduled to be held in Virginia on May 29, 1778.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 1, 1779.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The delegate from Albemarle County Thomas Jefferson defeated the president of the Council of State John Page.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia Patrick Henry was ineligible for re-election due to term limits established by the Constitution of Virginia.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election was conducted by the Virginia General Assembly in joint session.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] No candidate had a majority after the first count, requiring a second ballot between the two top-finishers.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 2, 1780.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia Thomas Jefferson was re-elected.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Senate and the House of Delegates met separately on June 1 to nominate candidates for governor; more than one nomination was made, requiring a vote of the Virginia General Assembly.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] When the Assembly met in joint session the following day, Jefferson was selected by the majority of members on the first ballot, although the names of the other candidates and the votes tallied were not recorded.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1782-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on November 20, 1782.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1782-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia Benjamin Harrison V was re-elected.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1782-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The House of Delegates met on November 19 to make nominations for governor and other offices, which the Senate accepted without amendment; the rule disqualifying votes for candidates other than those nominated was repealed prior to the balloting.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1782-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Harrison was selected by a majority of members on the first ballot; the official record of the proceedings does not include the names or tallied votes for any other candidates.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1783-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on November 27, 1783.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1783-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The House of Delegates met on November 26 to make nominations for governor and other offices, which the Senate accepted without amendment.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1783-virginia-gubernatorial-election] On the day of the election, Harrison was selected by a majority of members on the first ballot; the official record of the proceedings does not include the names or tallied votes for any other candidates.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The **1964 United States presidential election in Virginia** took place on November 3, 1964.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] All 50 states and the District of Columbia were part of the 1964 United States presidential election.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Virginia voters chose 12 electors to the Electoral College, which selected the president and vice president of the United States.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] For the previous six decades Virginia had almost completely disenfranchised its black and poor white populations through the use of a cumulative poll tax and literacy tests.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] So restricted was suffrage in this period that it has been calculated that a third of Virginia's electorate during the first half of the twentieth century comprised state employees and officeholders.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] This limited electorate allowed Virginian politics to be controlled for four decades by the Byrd Organization, as progressive “antiorganization” factions were rendered impotent by the inability of almost all their potential electorate to vote.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Opposition to the black civil rights legislation of Harry S.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Truman meant that the Byrd Organization did not support Adlai Stevenson II or John F.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Although the Organization viewed the national Republican party as no better on civil rights—it opposed the “massive resistance” orchestrated by Senator Byrd after *Brown v.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Board of Education*—Byrd's silence helped Eisenhower and Nixon win the state three consecutive times between 1952 and 1960.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] For 1964, it was evident that Virginia's electorate would be substantially increased by the Twenty-fourth Amendment, which banned the poll tax in federal elections and allowed major increases in voter registration during the preceding year.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Efforts by civil rights groups to register black voters would help black voter registration double vis-à-vis 1960.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] At the same time, Republican nominee Arizona Senator Barry Goldwater voted against the Civil Rights Act and targeted the South as critical to winning the election against incumbent President Lyndon B.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Johnson who signed that Act in August 1964, whilst most Byrd Democrats endorsed Johnson—this being the first time since 1936 the Organization had done so.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Virginia would not vote for a Democrat again until 2008, after which it has always gone Democratic.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Virginia was won by Johnson with 53.54 percent of the vote, making this the first time since 1948 that Virginia backed a Democratic presidential candidate.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Johnson won the national election in a landslide with 61.05 percent of the vote, which actually made Virginia Goldwater's tenth-best state nationally, 15.22 percentage points more Republican than the nation at large.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Johnson's victory saw major changes in Virginia voting patterns compared to previous presidential elections.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Despite the state shifting from Richard Nixon to Johnson, nine counties in the Southside region, which had been the stronghold of the Byrd Organization, shifted from Kennedy to Goldwater due to opposition to Johnson's civil rights proposals by an almost exclusively white electorate.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] In Charlotte County, Johnson lost 29 points from John F.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Despite this, a majority of white Virginians undoubtedly backed Goldwater, and a doubling of a black presidential vote that almost unanimously supported Johnson was critical for his win.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] As of the 2024 presidential election, this remains the last occasion when Amherst County, Bland County, Clarke County, Culpeper County, Fauquier County, Frederick County, Rockingham County, Washington County, York County and the city of Waynesboro have voted for a Democratic presidential candidate.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Prince William County and Winchester City would not vote Democratic again until 2008.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Fairfax County, Virginia's most populous county, would not vote Democratic again until 2004, having previously voted Democratic in 1940.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The independent city of Virginia Beach would not vote Democratic again until 2020.
[src:1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1964-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] This also remains the last time that Virginia and neighboring West Virginia would simultaneously vote Democratic in a presidential election.
